ot;, because Krishna said I am &quot;Om&quot; among mantras? Of course, not.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;B=\r\nR&gt;&gt; Same thing holds to japam vs other sadhanas such as homam.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;=\r\nBR&gt;&gt; Just as one may need ropes and other gear to climb mount everest, o=\r\nne may need to employ mantras other than &quot;Om&quot; and practices other than &quot;jap=\r\nam&quot; to overcome one&#39;s short-comings and reach the summit of the absolute, r=\r\nepresented by Om (and all other things mentioned by Krishna).&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&=\r\ngt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; When you do an external sacrifical ritual such a=\r\ns homam, your body is engaging in\n actions. So your mind has to be attached=\r\n to the body and use it in a particular way. Can one reach samadhi while do=\r\ning homam? Unlikely. One is more likely to reach samadhi when one stops the=\r\n external actions. Mind may be withdrawn completely from the body and absor=\r\nb fully in the mantra at some stage then.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; From the point o=\r\nf view, japam (sitting still and meditating on a mantra) is the ultimate sa=\r\ndhana.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; However, not everyone can reach god like that. Ther=\r\ne are so many vasanas (conditioning) in the mind that needs to be purged/pu=\r\nrified slowly. Until that is done, japam may not help one reach god. Until =\r\nthen, taking the help of an external pure object (such as fire) that has a =\r\npurifying effect on one&#39;s subtle consciousness can be helpful. It *prepares=\r\n* one for good japam.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; A lot of prie=\r\nsts do homam and then leave the fire and go away. In the homam manuals, I h=\r\nave made it a point to\n insist that people do japam with their favorite man=\r\ntra at the end of the homam, while sitting still with closed eyes. The idea=\r\n is that homam purifies subtle consciousness and *prepares* one for reachin=\r\ng god, while it is finally japam that takes one to god. After every homam, =\r\none&#39;s internal purity is at a maximum (a local maximum, temporally speaking=\r\n - sorry for the technical jargon) and japam will be more fruitful than at =\r\nother times.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Now onto other questio=\r\nns:&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; (1) It is unfruitful in the sense that it does not tak=\r\ne you closer to god. It is fruitful in the sense that it stops you from goi=\r\nng much further away from god. After all, if you weren&#39;t engaged in that ja=\r\npam and you were doing some other activity, probably your mind will wander =\r\neven more.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; I suggest looking at disturbing thoughts in the=\r\n middle of a japam as a heckler interrupting your speech. Instead of arguin=\r\ng and fighting\n with the heckler, simply take note of him, pause for a seco=\r\nnd and move on. Instead of panicking or worrying, simply take note of your =\r\nthoughts, pause for a second and move on.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; (2) Mantra means=\r\n that which protects (tra) the mind (mana). Various vasanas (conditioning) =\r\nare pulling the mind in different directions to react to various situations=\r\n in various ways and that activity tires out the mind. You protect it by an=\r\nchoring it in a mantra and teaching it to overcome the pulls of vasana.&lt;BR&gt;=\r\n&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; The proof of whether a mantra or japam or homam is working fo=\r\nr you or not is whether there is a slow internal transformation in you or n=\r\not, whether your internal reaction to various external things is changing f=\r\nor the better or not.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; (3) Difficult. This is where a good =\r\nguru is helpful.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Actually, in this age, technical perfecti=\r\non is almost ruled out. I suggest doing whatever one does with a sense of s=\r\nurrender\n and humility. If there is something partly correct that somebody =\r\nis doing, it will slowly increase with time and Nature will remove imperfec=\r\ntions with time.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; (4) I can write Obama&#39;s name and Gordon&#39;s=\r\n name on sheets of paper next to me and pretend that they came there and sa=\r\nt there. Will they really do it? On the other hand, if I am a world leader =\r\nholding a summit, probably I can make them actually come and sit there.&lt;BR&gt;=\r\n&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Nyasa means placement. When you do nyasa, you place various v=\r\nibrations (sound patterns) or energies (deities) in various body parts. For=\r\n most of us with distracted minds, it is merely a formality and means nothi=\r\nng. Only a sadhaka with a pure, pointed and focused mind can actually place=\r\n various vibrations and energies in various body parts.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; I =\r\nalways suggest to people to do nyasa as taught by elders (so that the knowl=\r\nedge lives and is passed on), but not worry too much about it.&lt;BR&gt;&gt;\n &lt;BR=\r\n&gt;&gt; As I said, we are in the midst of deepening Kali and the level of sad=\r\nhakas is not as high as in the old days. Technical perfection will become r=\r\narer and rarer. It is better to focus on surrender and humility.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;B=\r\nR&gt;&gt; Best regards,&lt;BR&gt;&gt; Narasimha&lt;BR&gt;&gt; ------------ --------- -----=\r\n---- --------- --------- --------- -&lt;BR&gt;&gt; Free Jyotish Software, Free Jy=\r\notish Lessons, Jyotish Writings,&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals fo=\r\nr short Homam and Pitri Tarpana:&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;A href=3D&quot;http://www.vedicast/&quot; t=\r\narget=3D_blank rel=3Dnofollow&gt;http://www.VedicAst&lt;/A&gt; rologer.org&lt;BR&gt;&gt; F=\r\nilms that make a difference: &lt;A href=3D&quot;http://saraswatifil/&quot; target=3D_bla=\r\nnk rel=3Dnofollow&gt;http://SaraswatiFil&lt;/A&gt; ms.org&lt;BR&gt;&gt; Spirituality: &lt;A h=\r\nref=3D&quot;http://groups./&quot; target=3D_blank rel=3Dnofollow&gt;